00:58:41.430 --> 00:58:46.180 align:middle line:84%
And then we can make connection
with the real experiments.

00:58:46.180 --> 00:58:46.887 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:58:46.887 --> 00:58:48.720 align:middle line:84%
To make connection with
the real experiment,

00:58:48.720 --> 00:58:51.930 align:middle line:84%
we need to develop
one more thing.

00:58:51.930 --> 00:58:55.240 align:middle line:84%
We need to develop
one more thing.

00:58:55.240 --> 00:59:01.080 align:middle line:84%
So we need to learn
how to calculate

00:59:01.080 --> 00:59:03.130 align:middle line:90%
the cross-section, OK?

00:59:03.130 --> 00:59:23.250 align:middle line:90%


00:59:23.250 --> 00:59:26.410 align:middle line:84%
So let's talk about how to
calculate the cross-section.

00:59:26.410 --> 00:59:33.030 align:middle line:90%
So this is a digression, OK?

00:59:33.030 --> 00:59:37.860 align:middle line:84%
So first, let's
remind you how we

00:59:37.860 --> 00:59:41.820 align:middle line:84%
define a cross-section in
nonrelativistic quantum

00:59:41.820 --> 00:59:42.630 align:middle line:90%
mechanics, OK?

00:59:42.630 --> 00:59:45.180 align:middle line:84%
In the scattering theory
of nonrelativistic quantum

00:59:45.180 --> 00:59:46.020 align:middle line:90%
mechanics.

00:59:46.020 --> 00:59:53.740 align:middle line:84%
So in nonrelativistic
quantum mechanics,

00:59:53.740 --> 00:59:57.220 align:middle line:90%
you consider there is a target.

00:59:57.220 --> 00:59:59.860 align:middle line:84%
The target is normally
considered to be a point, OK?

00:59:59.860 --> 01:00:04.070 align:middle line:84%
Here I just make it big
so that we can see it.

01:00:04.070 --> 01:00:08.210 align:middle line:90%
So here is the target.

01:00:08.210 --> 01:00:11.170 align:middle line:90%
And then we define our axis--

01:00:11.170 --> 01:00:14.750 align:middle line:84%
the scattering axis, which
the particle come in.

01:00:14.750 --> 01:00:17.425 align:middle line:84%
So this is some incident
beam of particle.

01:00:17.425 --> 01:00:24.960 align:middle line:90%


01:00:24.960 --> 01:00:26.650 align:middle line:90%
OK, coming into this direction.

01:00:26.650 --> 01:00:29.940 align:middle line:84%
So say this is a
Z-direction, OK?

01:00:29.940 --> 01:00:33.720 align:middle line:84%
And moving in this
direction to--

01:00:33.720 --> 01:00:36.990 align:middle line:84%
and then it will interact
with this particle.

01:00:36.990 --> 01:00:39.690 align:middle line:90%
And then it will scatter, OK?

01:00:39.690 --> 01:00:41.250 align:middle line:90%
So the particle will scatter.

01:00:41.250 --> 01:00:48.300 align:middle line:84%
And then we put the detector
around this target particle

01:00:48.300 --> 01:00:51.190 align:middle line:84%
to detect the
scattered particle.

01:00:51.190 --> 01:00:51.690 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:00:51.690 --> 01:00:53.520 align:middle line:90%
So for example, yeah.

01:00:53.520 --> 01:00:59.440 align:middle line:84%
So you should view
this solid angle here.

01:00:59.440 --> 01:00:59.940 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:00:59.940 --> 01:01:03.290 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
the phi direction.

01:01:03.290 --> 01:01:06.850 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
theta direction, OK?

01:01:06.850 --> 01:01:13.410 align:middle line:90%
So here is the theta direction.

01:01:13.410 --> 01:01:20.780 align:middle line:84%
And this is some small solid
angle, which the detector--

01:01:20.780 --> 01:01:22.850 align:middle line:84%
suppose there's a
detector here, OK?

01:01:22.850 --> 01:01:25.800 align:middle line:90%


01:01:25.800 --> 01:01:27.570 align:middle line:90%
Suppose there's a detector here.

01:01:27.570 --> 01:01:32.970 align:middle line:84%
And then this detector spread
the solid angle, D omega,

01:01:32.970 --> 01:01:35.910 align:middle line:90%
with respect to the target, OK?

01:01:35.910 --> 01:01:41.490 align:middle line:84%
So this is the standard
setup for nonrelativistic--

01:01:41.490 --> 01:01:45.540 align:middle line:84%
scattering process in the
nonrelativistic quantum

01:01:45.540 --> 01:01:47.940 align:middle line:90%
mechanics.

01:01:47.940 --> 01:02:04.630 align:middle line:84%
So what we measure is dN
dt outgoing particle, OK?

01:02:04.630 --> 01:02:08.920 align:middle line:84%
Scattered particle in the
theta and phi direction, OK?

01:02:08.920 --> 01:02:11.750 align:middle line:90%
So this is theta and phi.

01:02:11.750 --> 01:02:14.770 align:middle line:84%
This is where the detector
locates in the theta phi

01:02:14.770 --> 01:02:16.210 align:middle line:90%
direction.

01:02:16.210 --> 01:02:19.620 align:middle line:90%
So this is the number.

01:02:19.620 --> 01:02:24.740 align:middle line:84%
So this dN dt is the
number of particles--

01:02:24.740 --> 01:02:36.850 align:middle line:84%
number of scattered particles,
number of scattered particles

01:02:36.850 --> 01:02:37.510 align:middle line:90%
in --

01:02:37.510 --> 01:02:45.945 align:middle line:90%
per unit time in the detector.

01:02:45.945 --> 01:02:49.430 align:middle line:90%


01:02:49.430 --> 01:02:52.880 align:middle line:84%
It means registered by
the detector, detected

01:02:52.880 --> 01:02:58.910 align:middle line:84%
by the detector at the
location theta phi, OK?

01:02:58.910 --> 01:03:02.585 align:middle line:90%


01:03:02.585 --> 01:03:03.085 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:03:03.085 --> 01:03:06.650 align:middle line:90%


01:03:06.650 --> 01:03:12.618 align:middle line:84%
So the quantity we
measure is this quantity.

01:03:12.618 --> 01:03:13.910 align:middle line:90%
We just put the detector there.

01:03:13.910 --> 01:03:17.270 align:middle line:90%
We just measure particles, OK?

01:03:17.270 --> 01:03:22.810 align:middle line:84%
And clearly, so this scene
depends on many things, OK?

01:03:22.810 --> 01:03:24.400 align:middle line:84%
This quantity depends
on many things,

01:03:24.400 --> 01:03:30.980 align:middle line:84%
depends on the interaction
between the incident particle

01:03:30.980 --> 01:03:32.900 align:middle line:90%
and the target, et cetera.

01:03:32.900 --> 01:03:36.710 align:middle line:84%
But they also depend on many
other kinematic factors, OK?

01:03:36.710 --> 01:03:43.630 align:middle line:84%
So for example, it will
depend on -- this out--

01:03:43.630 --> 01:03:48.940 align:middle line:84%
clearly, it will depend on the
number of incident particles.

01:03:48.940 --> 01:03:53.480 align:middle line:90%


01:03:53.480 --> 01:03:53.980 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:03:53.980 --> 01:03:55.810 align:middle line:84%
So this is the number
of incident particles

01:03:55.810 --> 01:03:56.605 align:middle line:90%
per unit time.

01:03:56.605 --> 01:04:08.820 align:middle line:90%


01:04:08.820 --> 01:04:11.020 align:middle line:84%
If you have more incident
particles, of course,

01:04:11.020 --> 01:04:14.850 align:middle line:84%
you will detect more
outgoing particles, OK?

01:04:14.850 --> 01:04:17.760 align:middle line:84%
And of course, this will also
be proportional to D omega,

01:04:17.760 --> 01:04:23.800 align:middle line:84%
the solid angle extended
by the detector.

01:04:23.800 --> 01:04:25.810 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a larger
detector, of course,

01:04:25.810 --> 01:04:28.260 align:middle line:84%
you will detect
more particles, OK?

01:04:28.260 --> 01:04:34.250 align:middle line:90%


01:04:34.250 --> 01:04:41.990 align:middle line:84%
And then if we divide it by
those obvious kinematic factors

01:04:41.990 --> 01:04:44.930 align:middle line:84%
away, then we will
get something more

01:04:44.930 --> 01:04:48.050 align:middle line:84%
intrinsic to the
interactions, OK?

01:04:48.050 --> 01:05:11.450 align:middle line:90%
So we can consider--

01:05:11.450 --> 01:05:14.170 align:middle line:90%


01:05:14.170 --> 01:05:16.404 align:middle line:84%
we can divide by D omega
and divide it by this thing.

01:05:16.404 --> 01:05:21.640 align:middle line:90%
So this object, dN dt.

01:05:21.640 --> 01:05:26.650 align:middle line:84%
Then we divide it by D
omega per solid angle out

01:05:26.650 --> 01:05:29.830 align:middle line:84%
and divide it by
the incident number

01:05:29.830 --> 01:05:32.750 align:middle line:90%
of particles per unit time.

01:05:32.750 --> 01:05:44.810 align:middle line:84%
So this should give
us the probability

01:05:44.810 --> 01:06:00.860 align:middle line:84%
of a particle to be scattered
to theta phi direction, OK?

01:06:00.860 --> 01:06:05.900 align:middle line:84%
So this is the quantity
which captures the effect

01:06:05.900 --> 01:06:07.760 align:middle line:90%
of the interaction, OK?

01:06:07.760 --> 01:06:09.920 align:middle line:84%
So this is a more
intrinsic quantity.

01:06:09.920 --> 01:06:14.100 align:middle line:90%


01:06:14.100 --> 01:06:16.290 align:middle line:84%
But experimentally,
this is actually

01:06:16.290 --> 01:06:21.470 align:middle line:84%
not the thing we directly
measure in the experiment

01:06:21.470 --> 01:06:22.940 align:middle line:84%
because in the
experiment, it's not

01:06:22.940 --> 01:06:26.240 align:middle line:84%
easy to count the number of
the incident particles, OK?

01:06:26.240 --> 01:06:30.600 align:middle line:84%
We always consider
a beam of particles.

01:06:30.600 --> 01:06:33.810 align:middle line:84%
We always consider a
large number of particles,

01:06:33.810 --> 01:06:36.760 align:middle line:90%
a beam of particles.

01:06:36.760 --> 01:06:41.460 align:middle line:84%
So experimentally,
it's more convenient.

01:06:41.460 --> 01:06:49.400 align:middle line:90%


01:06:49.400 --> 01:06:52.150 align:middle line:90%
We often use the incident flux.

01:06:52.150 --> 01:06:57.580 align:middle line:90%


01:06:57.580 --> 01:07:09.740 align:middle line:84%
It's the number of particles
per unit time and per unit area,

01:07:09.740 --> 01:07:10.340 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:07:10.340 --> 01:07:11.810 align:middle line:90%
So we just send the beam.

01:07:11.810 --> 01:07:14.300 align:middle line:84%
And we just need to know
the density of the beam, OK?

01:07:14.300 --> 01:07:18.980 align:middle line:84%
So that will give us
the flux, the number

01:07:18.980 --> 01:07:22.350 align:middle line:84%
of particles ingoing per
unit time and per unit area.

01:07:22.350 --> 01:07:28.470 align:middle line:84%
So A is the cross-section
of the incident beam, OK?

01:07:28.470 --> 01:07:30.290 align:middle line:90%
So now, this is the quantity.

01:07:30.290 --> 01:07:32.320 align:middle line:90%
And now, we have to divide--

01:07:32.320 --> 01:07:35.140 align:middle line:84%
so instead of dividing by this
one, we divide by this one.

01:07:35.140 --> 01:07:35.640 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:07:35.640 --> 01:07:46.790 align:middle line:84%
So now, this D sigma D omega,
which is defined to be dN

01:07:46.790 --> 01:07:51.790 align:middle line:90%
dt D omega out--

01:07:51.790 --> 01:07:54.940 align:middle line:84%
and then you divide it
by incident flux, OK?

01:07:54.940 --> 01:07:58.890 align:middle line:90%


01:07:58.890 --> 01:08:02.860 align:middle line:90%
Incident flux per unit time, OK?

01:08:02.860 --> 01:08:08.310 align:middle line:84%
So that's the object we
actually measure, OK?

01:08:08.310 --> 01:08:14.590 align:middle line:90%
So some comments on this.

01:08:14.590 --> 01:08:18.269 align:middle line:84%
So the first comment is that
this has dimension of area.

01:08:18.269 --> 01:08:26.890 align:middle line:90%


01:08:26.890 --> 01:08:30.250 align:middle line:84%
So because this thing
is dimensionless--

01:08:30.250 --> 01:08:32.800 align:middle line:84%
this thing is dimensionless
because T canceled,

01:08:32.800 --> 01:08:35.109 align:middle line:90%
but now, we have divided by dA.

01:08:35.109 --> 01:08:36.649 align:middle line:90%
So A is going up.

01:08:36.649 --> 01:08:38.649 align:middle line:84%
And then this has
dimension of area.

01:08:38.649 --> 01:08:41.899 align:middle line:90%


01:08:41.899 --> 01:08:45.470 align:middle line:84%
So the physical
meaning of this, which

01:08:45.470 --> 01:08:50.029 align:middle line:84%
I'm sure you learned in
your nonrelativistic quantum

01:08:50.029 --> 01:09:00.250 align:middle line:84%
mechanics class, is that this
gives you the physical meaning

01:09:00.250 --> 01:09:02.750 align:middle line:90%
of this object.

01:09:02.750 --> 01:09:18.279 align:middle line:84%
So this gives you the effective
area of interaction, OK?

01:09:18.279 --> 01:09:20.939 align:middle line:90%


01:09:20.939 --> 01:09:27.010 align:middle line:84%
So heuristically, you can
imagine the following.

01:09:27.010 --> 01:09:30.942 align:middle line:84%
So if you imagine the
incident particle,

01:09:30.942 --> 01:09:33.359 align:middle line:84%
this target particle-- they
actually have some short range

01:09:33.359 --> 01:09:34.710 align:middle line:90%
interaction, OK?

01:09:34.710 --> 01:09:38.910 align:middle line:84%
And then they no
longer interact, say,

01:09:38.910 --> 01:09:40.770 align:middle line:90%
outside some distance.

01:09:40.770 --> 01:09:43.800 align:middle line:84%
And then heuristically,
then this quantity then

01:09:43.800 --> 01:09:51.810 align:middle line:84%
can be considered as-- give
you the area of interaction

01:09:51.810 --> 01:09:56.770 align:middle line:90%
around this target particle, OK?

01:09:56.770 --> 01:09:58.330 align:middle line:90%
Around the target particle.

01:09:58.330 --> 01:10:03.220 align:middle line:84%
So that's why this D
sigma D omega is called

01:10:03.220 --> 01:10:04.780 align:middle line:90%
the differential cross-section.

01:10:04.780 --> 01:10:14.420 align:middle line:90%


01:10:14.420 --> 01:10:19.220 align:middle line:84%
So the area which is going into
the direction of theta phi--

01:10:19.220 --> 01:10:23.120 align:middle line:84%
and the sigma total,
which is defined

01:10:23.120 --> 01:10:27.510 align:middle line:84%
to be D sigma, D omega-- you
integrate them over all angles,

01:10:27.510 --> 01:10:28.010 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:10:28.010 --> 01:10:30.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is a function
of theta and phi.

01:10:30.530 --> 01:10:33.270 align:middle line:84%
And now, you integrate
over all solid angles.

01:10:33.270 --> 01:10:35.420 align:middle line:84%
And then that gives you
the total cross-section.

01:10:35.420 --> 01:10:44.060 align:middle line:90%


01:10:44.060 --> 01:10:44.600 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:10:44.600 --> 01:10:51.840 align:middle line:84%
And to see this effective
area of interaction,

01:10:51.840 --> 01:10:56.100 align:middle line:84%
can be seen in the very
simple classical example.

01:10:56.100 --> 01:10:58.350 align:middle line:84%
So this definition actually
is not quantum mechanical.

01:10:58.350 --> 01:11:00.000 align:middle line:84%
You can also do it
classically, OK?

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:03.060 align:middle line:84%
It's not restricted
to quantum mechanics.

01:11:03.060 --> 01:11:06.160 align:middle line:84%
This can be defined for
any scattering event,

01:11:06.160 --> 01:11:08.970 align:middle line:84%
including in
classical mechanics.

01:11:08.970 --> 01:11:20.130 align:middle line:90%


01:11:20.130 --> 01:11:29.570 align:middle line:84%
So for example, if you
have classical scattering,

01:11:29.570 --> 01:11:38.970 align:middle line:84%
say, of some bullets,
off a billiard ball,

01:11:38.970 --> 01:11:42.330 align:middle line:84%
and then you find
the sigma total--

01:11:42.330 --> 01:11:45.960 align:middle line:84%
so suppose you have
classical scattering, OK?

01:11:45.960 --> 01:11:48.660 align:middle line:84%
And then you find
the sigma total.

01:11:48.660 --> 01:11:50.460 align:middle line:90%
It's just the cross-section.

01:11:50.460 --> 01:11:56.130 align:middle line:84%
It's just the total
area, total surface area.

01:11:56.130 --> 01:11:56.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:11:56.670 --> 01:11:57.360 align:middle line:90%
No.

01:11:57.360 --> 01:12:05.180 align:middle line:84%
It's the cross-section area
over the billiards, OK?

01:12:05.180 --> 01:12:11.910 align:middle line:90%


01:12:11.910 --> 01:12:14.982 align:middle line:84%
Because classically, when
you hit the billiard ball,

01:12:14.982 --> 01:12:16.440 align:middle line:84%
then you hit the
billiard ball, OK?

01:12:16.440 --> 01:12:18.240 align:middle line:84%
If you don't hit
the billiard ball,

01:12:18.240 --> 01:12:20.280 align:middle line:90%
then you don't change direction.

01:12:20.280 --> 01:12:23.130 align:middle line:84%
And then the total
cross-section just

01:12:23.130 --> 01:12:27.180 align:middle line:84%
is the cross-section of
the billiard ball, OK?

01:12:27.180 --> 01:12:33.390 align:middle line:84%
And so when you go
to quantum theory,

01:12:33.390 --> 01:12:35.940 align:middle line:84%
then this is the heuristic
way you understand

01:12:35.940 --> 01:12:40.830 align:middle line:84%
there's some kind of effective
cross-section for this target,

01:12:40.830 --> 01:12:41.430 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:12:41.430 --> 01:12:46.710 align:middle line:84%
And outside that area
then you no longer have--

01:12:46.710 --> 01:12:47.610 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

01:12:47.610 --> 01:12:50.820 align:middle line:84%
Heuristically, you no
longer have interactions.

01:12:50.820 --> 01:12:51.510 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:51.510 --> 01:12:56.610 align:middle line:84%
So now, let me just
make two quick remarks

01:12:56.610 --> 01:12:58.065 align:middle line:90%
in a relativistic theory.

01:12:58.065 --> 01:13:02.850 align:middle line:90%


01:13:02.850 --> 01:13:05.590 align:middle line:90%
So now, we can generalize.

01:13:05.590 --> 01:13:10.550 align:middle line:84%
So this discussion is in
the nonrelativistic context.

01:13:10.550 --> 01:13:12.940 align:middle line:84%
So in the relativistic
context, we essentially just

01:13:12.940 --> 01:13:20.630 align:middle line:84%
have D sigma cross-section from
initial state to final state,

01:13:20.630 --> 01:13:21.130 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:13:21.130 --> 01:13:23.620 align:middle line:84%
We no longer have-- so
this is very specific.

01:13:23.620 --> 01:13:27.000 align:middle line:84%
We have one particle
scattering the other particle.

01:13:27.000 --> 01:13:29.880 align:middle line:84%
And this particle
scatters away, OK?

01:13:29.880 --> 01:13:33.870 align:middle line:84%
But in relativistic, you
can have two particles.

01:13:33.870 --> 01:13:36.840 align:middle line:84%
You can create
10,000 particles, OK?

01:13:36.840 --> 01:13:40.320 align:middle line:84%
And so this language
no longer works, OK?

01:13:40.320 --> 01:13:43.230 align:middle line:84%
So but still, you can define
some kind of cross-section

01:13:43.230 --> 01:13:47.890 align:middle line:84%
of initial state alpha to
some final state beta, OK?

01:13:47.890 --> 01:13:52.900 align:middle line:84%
And so we will be interested
in the situation in which we

01:13:52.900 --> 01:13:55.030 align:middle line:90%
have two initial particles, OK?

01:13:55.030 --> 01:14:01.360 align:middle line:84%
Because experimentally,
it's convenient just

01:14:01.360 --> 01:14:03.040 align:middle line:84%
to have two
particles scattering.

01:14:03.040 --> 01:14:04.660 align:middle line:84%
So you have two
initial particles.

01:14:04.660 --> 01:14:13.390 align:middle line:84%
But final state, in principle,
can be arbitrary, OK?

01:14:13.390 --> 01:14:18.960 align:middle line:90%
And so this object--

01:14:18.960 --> 01:14:20.890 align:middle line:84%
since, in the
relativistic theory,

01:14:20.890 --> 01:14:27.212 align:middle line:84%
this should be physically
observable, so this should be--

01:14:27.212 --> 01:14:29.670 align:middle line:84%
so because this essentially is
a measure of the probability

01:14:29.670 --> 01:14:32.930 align:middle line:84%
of the scattering,
so we require this

01:14:32.930 --> 01:14:38.961 align:middle line:90%
object to be Lorentz invariant.

01:14:38.961 --> 01:14:46.040 align:middle line:90%


01:14:46.040 --> 01:14:47.450 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:14:47.450 --> 01:14:52.760 align:middle line:84%
And also, in the relativistic,
we just scatter two particles.

01:14:52.760 --> 01:14:54.500 align:middle line:84%
There's no notion of
what is the target

01:14:54.500 --> 01:14:56.990 align:middle line:84%
or what is the
incident particle.

01:14:56.990 --> 01:14:59.240 align:middle line:84%
So these two particles
should have equal rho.

01:14:59.240 --> 01:15:08.040 align:middle line:84%
So this should be
symmetric in 1 2, OK?

01:15:08.040 --> 01:15:10.260 align:middle line:84%
So if you exchange 1
2, this cross-section

01:15:10.260 --> 01:15:12.020 align:middle line:90%
should be the same.

01:15:12.020 --> 01:15:12.520 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:15:12.520 --> 01:15:15.470 align:middle line:90%
It should be the same.

01:15:15.470 --> 01:15:18.820 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you consider--
but you can always

01:15:18.820 --> 01:15:22.180 align:middle line:84%
consider in the rest frame,
say, of particle 2, OK?

01:15:22.180 --> 01:15:27.265 align:middle line:84%
So suppose we consider
the rest frame.

01:15:27.265 --> 01:15:30.390 align:middle line:90%


01:15:30.390 --> 01:15:35.120 align:middle line:84%
Suppose we go into the
rest frame of particle 2.

01:15:35.120 --> 01:15:40.010 align:middle line:84%
And then we roughly
have this situation, OK?

01:15:40.010 --> 01:15:41.630 align:middle line:90%
So this is particle 2.

01:15:41.630 --> 01:15:44.820 align:middle line:84%
This is the particle 1,
which comes to particle 2.

01:15:44.820 --> 01:15:53.520 align:middle line:84%
And then in this situation, we
can define the alpha to beta

01:15:53.520 --> 01:15:56.350 align:middle line:84%
based on our nonrelativistic
considerations.

01:15:56.350 --> 01:15:58.450 align:middle line:90%
And then we consider--

01:15:58.450 --> 01:16:07.990 align:middle line:84%
so here I use the probability
from alpha to beta dP, OK?

01:16:07.990 --> 01:16:12.970 align:middle line:84%
So this essentially
replaces that.

01:16:12.970 --> 01:16:13.600 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:16:13.600 --> 01:16:16.510 align:middle line:84%
Here the final particle
only has one particle.

01:16:16.510 --> 01:16:19.490 align:middle line:90%
So you can define a solid angle.

01:16:19.490 --> 01:16:24.370 align:middle line:84%
But if we have 10,000 particles
here in the beta, of course,

01:16:24.370 --> 01:16:25.960 align:middle line:84%
I cannot define a
solid angle, OK?

01:16:25.960 --> 01:16:30.370 align:middle line:84%
So I can just talk about
probability from alpha to beta,

01:16:30.370 --> 01:16:31.720 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:16:31.720 --> 01:16:34.390 align:middle line:84%
From alpha to beta,
but per unit time.

01:16:34.390 --> 01:16:40.120 align:middle line:84%
And then again, we divide it
by the incident flux of 1.

01:16:40.120 --> 01:16:43.550 align:middle line:90%


01:16:43.550 --> 01:16:44.690 align:middle line:90%
OK?

01:16:44.690 --> 01:16:47.940 align:middle line:90%
The incident flux of 1, OK?

01:16:47.940 --> 01:16:48.510 align:middle line:90%
Oh.

01:16:48.510 --> 01:16:51.710 align:middle line:90%
And let me just call it in.

01:16:51.710 --> 01:16:56.690 align:middle line:84%
And 1 means the number
of particles of 1, OK?

01:16:56.690 --> 01:16:59.390 align:middle line:90%
So yeah.

01:16:59.390 --> 01:17:04.160 align:middle line:84%
So what we will do
is that we will first

01:17:04.160 --> 01:17:08.540 align:middle line:84%
calculate this object
in the rest frame of 2.

01:17:08.540 --> 01:17:13.460 align:middle line:84%
And then we construct the
Lorentz invariant version

01:17:13.460 --> 01:17:15.140 align:middle line:90%
of this, OK?

01:17:15.140 --> 01:17:19.490 align:middle line:84%
So that's our strategy
to define what

01:17:19.490 --> 01:17:21.540 align:middle line:84%
will be the relativistic
generalization of this.

01:17:21.540 --> 01:17:22.040 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:22.040 --> 01:17:25.960 align:middle line:84%
So we will discuss
this next time.

